In the original, however, it gives a very pleasing air to the clause,as marking a continuance of action in the two particular cases to which he refers. The poet intends to convey the following idea: The man who wishes to obtain a favour at the hands of the great and power- ful, should, above all things, display a modest deportment, and one far removed from importunate solicitation.--46. indotata mihi soror est, &a ‘⁴ The man who tells his patron, ‘ My sister has no portion, my mother is in straitened circumstances, and my farm is neither saleable nor to be relied upon for my support,' eries out, in effect, Give me food.''—48.
